I was involved (as R&amp;D manager for a major components supplier) in this
program about 20 years ago. I thought then, and still do now, that it is an
overcomplicated system, and that it broke so much new ground that the USMC
would not be competent to manage its development. Both opinions were
sustained by events. The program should have been killed.

Nevertheless let's not prejudge the V-22 now that it has finally reached
deployment. The capabilities it provides are significant, and I do agree
that they are needed and will be valuable. The limitations that remain are
distressing but not necessarily crippling. Other aircraft have operated with
similar constraints before. A lot of people were killed during development
of the helicopter, and several other groundbreaking technologies.

Although I don't think the program was worth the time and money spent or
losing the two or three types of advanced helicopters that could have been
developed instead, the V-22 is not necessarily going to turn out to be a
failure in service. It can fly much faster and farther than a helicopter,
and I don't see why it can't receive the armament that is now lacking as a
future upgrade.

Perhaps the greatest benefit from this effort is that it will someday be
possible to develop a successor to the V-22 that will really demonstrate the
full potential of tilt-rotor technology.

Remember the F-111? Another developmental boondoggle that after a great deal
of cost escalation and mismanagement, turned out to be a very fine aircraft
in service.

