Not even close, Ken.
The CL-84 first flew in May of 1965, with the first aircraft lost in
Sept.'67
The second CL-84 first flew in Feb. 1970, and was lost August of '73.
The third was flown in '73 or '73, and was retired in '74, IIRC.
Both losses were structural failures of propeller/gearbox systems, luckily
high enough and fast enough for the crews to punch out.

Compare and contrast to the Hiller X-18 First flight Nov 1959, retired July
1961
and the Hiller/LTV XC-142A
5 built- first flight Sept '64, 1st complete VTo/Transition/Transition/VL
Jan '65
1 lost on 5/67, (3 fatalities), rest retired in 1970.
The XC-142 was, in fact, a functional transport aircraft, capable of hauling
payloads of more than 10,000#, and qualified aboard Aircraft Carrier, LPH's
and LSD's.

I don't know what the CL.84 would have done for Pres. Carter - there were
plenty of other ways for him to run for the border, if so desired.  (Many,
in fact, would have offered to give him a lift.)  If you're talking about
the Iranian Rescue Mission, you're passing balloon gas, unless you can
establish that the CL-84 would have been impervious to sandstorms, and
capable of bouncing off of a C-130 without damaging either aircraft.

